1
00:00:08,750 --> 00:00:10,333
[judge] Court is now in session.

2
00:00:10,416 --> 00:00:12,208
[tense music playing]

3
00:00:12,291 --> 00:00:13,875
Defendant, step forward.

4
00:00:16,041 --> 00:00:19,416
[man] <i>A lawyer upholds human rights.</i>

5
00:00:21,166 --> 00:00:23,875
<i>A lawyer's duty is to serve people.</i>

6
00:00:23,958 --> 00:00:25,208
I will now deliver the verdict.

7
00:00:25,291 --> 00:00:27,083
<i>However, they cannot serve everyone.</i>

8
00:00:27,166 --> 00:00:28,666
On the charge of first-degree assault…

9
00:00:29,250 --> 00:00:32,666
[man] <i>The only person a lawyer can protect</i>
<i>is their client,</i>

10
00:00:33,458 --> 00:00:36,291
<i>even if that client is someone</i>
<i>society calls the bad guy.</i>

11
00:00:36,375 --> 00:00:37,875
[judge] The court finds the defendant

12
00:00:38,458 --> 00:00:39,291
not guilty.

13
00:00:39,375 --> 00:00:40,708
- All right!
- Yeah!

14
00:00:40,791 --> 00:00:42,166
[judge] Order in the court!

15
00:00:42,750 --> 00:00:44,250
[man] <i>When you save one,</i>

16
00:00:44,333 --> 00:00:45,916
<i>you bring sorrow to another.</i>

17
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:48,000
You disgusting piece of shit!

18
00:00:48,083 --> 00:00:51,583
Why would you defend a monster like that?
How can you live with yourself?

19
00:00:51,666 --> 00:00:53,875
[judge] Order in the court, please.

20
00:00:53,958 --> 00:00:55,041
[woman crying]

21
00:00:55,125 --> 00:00:58,916
[man] <i>A lawyer must carry</i>
<i>the weight of this sin.</i>

22
00:01:00,375 --> 00:01:01,666
<i>Fact is…</i>

23
00:01:01,750 --> 00:01:03,166
[prosecutor] Attorney Kujo.

24
00:01:03,875 --> 00:01:07,708
So what? Is that why you're a lawyer?
To protect the scum of the earth?

25
00:01:08,666 --> 00:01:09,500
Hey!

26
00:01:10,958 --> 00:01:11,875
[man] <i>…good lawyers</i>

27
00:01:12,916 --> 00:01:14,250
<i>are bad people.</i>

28
00:01:14,333 --> 00:01:16,333
[upbeat music playing]

29
00:01:23,166 --> 00:01:24,500
[phone ringing]

30
00:01:28,958 --> 00:01:31,125
[man] Oh, hello? This is Karasuma.

31
00:01:34,791 --> 00:01:36,750
Uh, are you sure this map is right?

32
00:01:42,041 --> 00:01:42,875
Hello?

33
00:01:44,666 --> 00:01:46,541
Hello? Yakushimae?

34
00:01:46,625 --> 00:01:48,375
[Yakushimae] <i>Huh? Yeah, what's up?</i>

35
00:01:49,333 --> 00:01:52,583
Honestly, I've no idea where I'm going
with this map you drew.

36
00:01:52,666 --> 00:01:55,750
[Yakushimae] <i>What do you mean?</i>
<i>It's pretty detailed, isn't it?</i>

37
00:01:56,791 --> 00:01:58,083
I wouldn't call it detailed.

38
00:01:58,166 --> 00:01:59,833
[cries out, grunts]

39
00:01:59,916 --> 00:02:02,833
[Yakushimae] <i>See?</i>
<i>You just tripped, didn't you?</i>

40
00:02:02,916 --> 00:02:03,791
<i>It's on the map.</i>

41
00:02:03,875 --> 00:02:05,000
What?

42
00:02:05,583 --> 00:02:07,708
NARROW, LOTS OF CATS, TOILET,
WATCH OUT FOR WATER,

43
00:02:07,791 --> 00:02:08,916
SUPER NARROW UNEVEN SURFACE!

44
00:02:09,500 --> 00:02:12,416
Why don't you just give me
the address so I can use my phone?

45
00:02:12,500 --> 00:02:15,625
[Yakushimae] <i>No, really,</i>
<i>I'm telling you, this is the quickest way.</i>

46
00:02:15,708 --> 00:02:17,416
<i>Anyway, you're almost there.</i>

47
00:02:20,625 --> 00:02:22,000
[indistinct chatter]

48
00:02:26,291 --> 00:02:27,958
I found it. 21 New City Building.

49
00:02:28,041 --> 00:02:28,875
NEW CITY 21 BUILDING

50
00:02:28,958 --> 00:02:30,916
[Yakushimae] <i>Good, okay. Go inside.</i>

51
00:02:31,500 --> 00:02:32,750
[Karasuma] What? Really?

52
00:02:38,541 --> 00:02:39,958
Are you sure it's here?

53
00:02:40,458 --> 00:02:42,708
[Yakushimae] <i>Oh, oh! Sorry.</i>
<i>Listen, I've gotta go. Bye.</i>

54
00:02:42,791 --> 00:02:44,500
[Karasuma] No, wait a sec. Hello?

55
00:02:45,250 --> 00:02:46,083
Hello?

56
00:02:46,666 --> 00:02:47,666
Excuse me.

57
00:02:51,333 --> 00:02:52,166
[coughs]

58
00:03:05,666 --> 00:03:06,916
KUJO LAW OFFICE
THIS WAY 4F

59
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:08,375
[Karasuma] There it is.

60
00:03:35,041 --> 00:03:36,166
[music fades]

61
00:03:36,250 --> 00:03:40,875
KUJO LAW OFFICE
IF YOU NEED ME, I’M ON THE ROOF

62
00:03:40,958 --> 00:03:42,958
[siren wailing in the distance]

63
00:03:44,916 --> 00:03:45,875
[sighs]

64
00:03:49,791 --> 00:03:50,708
[huffs]

65
00:03:59,083 --> 00:04:01,166
[pan sizzling]

66
00:04:13,625 --> 00:04:15,833
Uh, are you… Attorney Kujo?

67
00:04:17,416 --> 00:04:19,041
Oh, I called you earlier.
I'm Karasuma, I--

68
00:04:19,125 --> 00:04:20,666
Just a moment, please.

69
00:04:35,958 --> 00:04:37,000
What are you…

70
00:04:37,500 --> 00:04:38,333
Cooking.

71
00:04:39,875 --> 00:04:41,541
Hamburger steak with a fried egg.

72
00:04:43,458 --> 00:04:44,333
Are you hungry?

73
00:04:44,916 --> 00:04:46,666
Uh, no. That's okay.

74
00:04:48,500 --> 00:04:50,333
Um, what is this?

75
00:04:50,833 --> 00:04:51,750
My house.

76
00:04:52,791 --> 00:04:53,666
House?

77
00:04:54,583 --> 00:04:56,166
This is my house, where I live.

78
00:05:04,708 --> 00:05:07,708
So, I was wondering if you had a chance
to take a look at my résumé?

79
00:05:07,791 --> 00:05:09,041
No. I didn't bother.

80
00:05:09,125 --> 00:05:09,958
Oh.

81
00:05:10,791 --> 00:05:12,791
But I heard about you from Yakushimae.

82
00:05:13,500 --> 00:05:16,291
Top graduate of the University of Tokyo,
Faculty of Law.

83
00:05:16,375 --> 00:05:19,583
Currently employed at one of the Big Four
law firms, Higashimura Yuhi Law.

84
00:05:21,666 --> 00:05:24,333
Why would someone with that kind
of résumé want to work with me?

85
00:05:29,958 --> 00:05:31,666
I don't know if you've seen this.

86
00:05:33,458 --> 00:05:34,708
CROOKED LAWYER TAIZA KUJO

87
00:05:34,791 --> 00:05:37,083
Do you know people call you
a crooked lawyer?

88
00:05:39,583 --> 00:05:42,541
All these gang-led fraud schemes,
violent assaults, murders…

89
00:05:43,208 --> 00:05:44,875
Not to put too fine a point on it,

90
00:05:45,375 --> 00:05:47,625
but why do you always defend the bad guys?

91
00:05:49,750 --> 00:05:51,125
[Kujo] Attorney Karasuma.

92
00:05:51,625 --> 00:05:52,500
Yes?

93
00:05:54,666 --> 00:05:56,750
Aren't I the one
who's supposed to be interviewing you?

94
00:05:57,958 --> 00:05:58,833
Oh.

95
00:05:59,333 --> 00:06:01,083
I didn't mean it like that.

96
00:06:13,291 --> 00:06:15,291
[tense music playing]

97
00:06:39,625 --> 00:06:41,416
Mibu!

98
00:06:41,500 --> 00:06:43,166
[Mibu] What're you doing here, Morita?

99
00:06:43,250 --> 00:06:44,625
I'm sorry. [chuckles]

100
00:06:44,708 --> 00:06:46,250
I had a bit of an accident,

101
00:06:46,333 --> 00:06:48,333
and I'm going on a drive
with my girlfriend,

102
00:06:48,416 --> 00:06:50,083
so I was hoping you could fix it?

103
00:06:50,958 --> 00:06:52,000
[Morita] Sorry.

104
00:06:52,916 --> 00:06:56,083
It's a hit-and-run, isn't it?
You're definitely gonna get caught.

105
00:06:56,166 --> 00:06:57,000
What?

106
00:06:57,083 --> 00:07:00,250
[Morita] This dent was caused by a crash
you tried to avoid but couldn't.

107
00:07:00,750 --> 00:07:01,833
The paint's chipped too.

108
00:07:02,916 --> 00:07:05,666
From that, they can get the color,
year, and model of the car.

109
00:07:09,208 --> 00:07:11,541
Your car might not have been caught
on camera at the site,

110
00:07:11,625 --> 00:07:14,208
but it was definitely caught
on camera in the area.

111
00:07:16,583 --> 00:07:18,291
Only a matter of time
before they catch you.

112
00:07:19,916 --> 00:07:20,791
[sighs worriedly]

113
00:07:20,875 --> 00:07:23,958
Oh my God!

114
00:07:24,041 --> 00:07:25,416
[gasps]

115
00:07:25,500 --> 00:07:27,541
What should I do then, Mibu, huh?

116
00:07:32,708 --> 00:07:34,541
I'm gonna introduce you to a lawyer.

117
00:07:38,791 --> 00:07:40,000
Thank you.

118
00:07:40,958 --> 00:07:42,500
[cell phone buzzes]

119
00:07:43,166 --> 00:07:44,250
Mr. Kujo?

120
00:07:45,333 --> 00:07:47,208
KENGO MIBU

121
00:07:48,416 --> 00:07:49,958
Hi. This is Kujo.

122
00:07:50,041 --> 00:07:51,291
Kujo, it's me.

123
00:07:52,208 --> 00:07:55,000
I've got a favor to ask of you,
and it's kind of urgent.

124
00:07:57,750 --> 00:07:59,666
Understood. That's fine.
I'll be waiting for you.

125
00:08:02,750 --> 00:08:03,875
Someone looking for a lawyer?

126
00:08:03,958 --> 00:08:04,833
[Kujo] Yeah.

127
00:08:05,916 --> 00:08:07,791
A traffic accident, apparently.

128
00:08:07,875 --> 00:08:09,000
What can I do?

129
00:08:10,083 --> 00:08:11,208
Oh, well…

130
00:08:12,125 --> 00:08:13,458
Uh…

131
00:08:14,916 --> 00:08:17,208
You can… take care of this.

132
00:08:17,875 --> 00:08:18,875
Huh?

133
00:08:18,958 --> 00:08:20,625
[Kujo] You just asked what you could do.

134
00:08:22,750 --> 00:08:23,791
Sink's over there.

135
00:08:45,958 --> 00:08:48,291
[Karasuma sighs] I'm done, Mr. Kujo.

136
00:08:48,375 --> 00:08:49,708
[Kujo] Okay, thank you.

137
00:08:50,708 --> 00:08:52,291
[Karasuma] Um, is this place…

138
00:08:53,208 --> 00:08:57,000
It used to be a nightclub.
I rented it as is and moved my stuff in.

139
00:08:57,541 --> 00:08:59,708
You can use the space over there
however you like.

140
00:09:00,208 --> 00:09:02,583
- Over here?
- Uh-huh.

141
00:09:08,500 --> 00:09:11,166
Oh, that's actually Yakushimae's
when she comes in.

142
00:09:11,833 --> 00:09:12,791
Yeah.

143
00:09:14,875 --> 00:09:15,708
[sighs]

144
00:09:28,291 --> 00:09:29,666
[door opening]

145
00:09:29,750 --> 00:09:31,750
Hey, Mr. Kujo. Sorry for the short notice.

146
00:09:31,833 --> 00:09:33,000
[Kujo] Oh.

147
00:09:33,083 --> 00:09:34,791
- Please.
- [Morita] Hmm.

148
00:09:36,541 --> 00:09:37,375
Who are you?

149
00:09:39,166 --> 00:09:41,625
My name is Karasuma. I'm a lawyer.

150
00:09:41,708 --> 00:09:43,000
A lawyer?

151
00:09:43,083 --> 00:09:44,500
[unsettling music playing]

152
00:09:44,583 --> 00:09:45,708
[Kujo] Rest assured.

153
00:09:46,708 --> 00:09:49,041
He's way more competent than I am.

154
00:09:50,750 --> 00:09:52,750
- Attorney Karasuma.
- Yes?

155
00:09:53,625 --> 00:09:56,000
- Make them some tea, would you?
- What?

156
00:10:00,833 --> 00:10:01,708
[Kujo] Please.

157
00:10:01,791 --> 00:10:02,625
Sure.

158
00:10:02,708 --> 00:10:04,041
[upbeat music playing]

159
00:10:06,875 --> 00:10:07,916
Oh, okay.

160
00:10:15,750 --> 00:10:17,083
[Kujo] So…

161
00:10:17,166 --> 00:10:18,750
You want to tell me what happened?

162
00:10:18,833 --> 00:10:20,250
Uh…

163
00:10:20,333 --> 00:10:21,250
Uh…

164
00:10:22,333 --> 00:10:23,208
Uh.

165
00:10:23,708 --> 00:10:25,083
- Morita.
- Huh?

166
00:10:26,375 --> 00:10:27,333
Tell him the truth.

167
00:10:28,416 --> 00:10:30,250
Uh… yeah, yeah. Yeah.

168
00:10:31,791 --> 00:10:32,666
I, uh…

169
00:10:33,625 --> 00:10:38,666
I was just driving, and I, uh,
accidentally, mmm, hit something.

170
00:10:39,541 --> 00:10:40,541
What exactly did you hit?

171
00:10:41,333 --> 00:10:42,750
Uh… uh…

172
00:10:43,416 --> 00:10:46,208
It was, uh… uh…

173
00:10:47,750 --> 00:10:49,166
[music builds]

174
00:10:53,250 --> 00:10:54,166
- [tires squeal]
- [thump]

175
00:11:00,833 --> 00:11:01,875
[music fades]

176
00:11:01,958 --> 00:11:03,833
[Kujo] Please be honest with me.

177
00:11:07,625 --> 00:11:09,958
A lawyer's primary duty

178
00:11:10,750 --> 00:11:12,625
is the protection of their clients.

179
00:11:15,125 --> 00:11:17,125
[theme music playing]

180
00:11:42,958 --> 00:11:44,958
Were you on the phone
when you had the accident?

181
00:11:45,541 --> 00:11:47,208
I, well… I--

182
00:11:47,291 --> 00:11:49,166
[Kujo] You smell like alcohol.

183
00:11:49,250 --> 00:11:50,375
Are you drunk?

184
00:11:50,875 --> 00:11:53,291
What? No, of course not. [nervous laugh]

185
00:11:53,375 --> 00:11:54,208
I…

186
00:11:54,708 --> 00:11:55,750
It's okay.

187
00:11:56,250 --> 00:11:58,375
It's just us. No one else is here.

188
00:12:03,416 --> 00:12:05,416
[water pouring]

189
00:12:09,708 --> 00:12:10,750
I'm sorry.

190
00:12:11,416 --> 00:12:14,833
Okay. I found a rare character in my game,
so I checked my phone.

191
00:12:15,875 --> 00:12:18,458
And yes, I was drinking this morning.

192
00:12:18,541 --> 00:12:21,291
On his phone and drunk…

193
00:12:21,375 --> 00:12:22,583
What a scumbag.

194
00:12:23,291 --> 00:12:24,375
[Kujo] Mr. Karasuma.

195
00:12:24,458 --> 00:12:27,000
If the police ask the game company
for their records,

196
00:12:27,083 --> 00:12:29,708
they'll be able to prove
when and where you were logged in.

197
00:12:29,791 --> 00:12:32,083
It's best if you don't mention
that you were playing a game.

198
00:12:32,166 --> 00:12:33,541
[Morita] Oh… okay.

199
00:12:33,625 --> 00:12:37,791
Uh, um, if the person I hit died,
would the charges be more serious?

200
00:12:37,875 --> 00:12:38,875
[sneezes]

201
00:12:39,833 --> 00:12:41,541
[sniffs] Sorry.

202
00:12:42,041 --> 00:12:43,583
I've got terrible allergies.

203
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:47,500
If you were driving under the influence
and looking at your phone,

204
00:12:47,583 --> 00:12:49,583
it'd be dangerous driving causing death.

205
00:12:49,666 --> 00:12:51,625
The maximum sentence is 20 years.

206
00:12:51,708 --> 00:12:54,791
But if it's negligent driving
causing death, it's a suspended sentence.

207
00:12:54,875 --> 00:12:57,583
Your future depends on whether
it's considered dangerous driving

208
00:12:57,666 --> 00:12:59,000
or negligent driving.

209
00:12:59,083 --> 00:13:00,041
[Kujo sniffs]

210
00:13:00,125 --> 00:13:01,666
You're in Mr. Kujo's hands now.

211
00:13:04,833 --> 00:13:06,333
[Morita] Oh God…

212
00:13:07,083 --> 00:13:09,666
[inhales sharply]
Mibu, why would you say that?

213
00:13:09,750 --> 00:13:12,541
What if I end up going away for 20 years?

214
00:13:13,375 --> 00:13:15,250
Shit. [gasps]

215
00:13:15,333 --> 00:13:18,083
I just really hope the guy I hit is alive.

216
00:13:20,208 --> 00:13:22,416
It can be problematic
if the victim gives a statement.

217
00:13:22,500 --> 00:13:24,333
Uh… Huh?

218
00:13:25,791 --> 00:13:27,916
So it's an advantage for you if he's dead.

219
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:29,708
- [tense music playing]
- [scoffs]

220
00:13:29,791 --> 00:13:31,958
Attorney Kujo,
that is messed up, seriously.

221
00:13:32,541 --> 00:13:34,458
[Kujo] There's no victim statement.

222
00:13:35,166 --> 00:13:37,958
And unless there's concrete evidence,
we can win.

223
00:13:38,041 --> 00:13:39,083
Give me your phone.

224
00:13:42,208 --> 00:13:44,625
I'm just gonna say a few things
to myself right now.

225
00:13:44,708 --> 00:13:46,083
[Morita] To yourself?

226
00:13:46,166 --> 00:13:48,041
There's a lot of evidence on a phone.

227
00:13:48,125 --> 00:13:49,958
We're gonna leave it right here.

228
00:13:50,041 --> 00:13:53,750
If the police ask you for your phone,
tell them you lost it, understand?

229
00:13:53,833 --> 00:13:54,833
Your wallet.

230
00:13:54,916 --> 00:13:55,958
[Morita grunts]

231
00:13:57,083 --> 00:13:59,333
If you have bar receipts in there,
throw them all away.

232
00:13:59,416 --> 00:14:00,958
[hesitatingly] Oh, okay.

233
00:14:01,750 --> 00:14:04,625
[Kujo] Turn yourself in
after the alcohol's out of your system.

234
00:14:04,708 --> 00:14:07,541
There's a medication called Tathion
that eliminates alcohol from the body.

235
00:14:07,625 --> 00:14:09,625
It's a pretty good drug
that even works for meth,

236
00:14:09,708 --> 00:14:11,875
but it's only prescribed in hospitals.

237
00:14:11,958 --> 00:14:12,958
So, uh…

238
00:14:13,625 --> 00:14:15,541
Go to a sauna and sweat it out.

239
00:14:15,625 --> 00:14:17,291
[Morita] Sauna. Got it.

240
00:14:18,541 --> 00:14:20,958
As long as you show up
at the police station with a lawyer,

241
00:14:21,041 --> 00:14:22,875
it'll count as turning yourself in.

242
00:14:24,041 --> 00:14:25,541
Listen, Mr. Morita.

243
00:14:26,250 --> 00:14:28,833
Regarding the details of the collision,
the exact location,

244
00:14:28,916 --> 00:14:30,333
the traffic light color, your speed,

245
00:14:30,416 --> 00:14:32,625
you're not gonna get into any specifics,
okay?

246
00:14:32,708 --> 00:14:37,000
That said, if you stay completely silent,
it's gonna look pretty suspicious.

247
00:14:37,708 --> 00:14:40,416
The safest approach is to acknowledge
there was a collision,

248
00:14:40,500 --> 00:14:43,916
but refrain from trying to describe
any verifiable details.

249
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:44,833
[Morita] Okay.

250
00:14:45,708 --> 00:14:48,375
During the interview,
when the police are questioning you,

251
00:14:48,458 --> 00:14:50,916
there's only one thing
you need to remember.

252
00:14:51,416 --> 00:14:52,250
[Morita] What?

253
00:14:54,458 --> 00:14:56,708
If you're not sure
if you should say something, don't.

254
00:14:57,875 --> 00:14:59,291
That's it.

255
00:15:00,541 --> 00:15:02,458
Count on me, sir. I got it.

256
00:15:03,375 --> 00:15:04,333
All right.

257
00:15:05,791 --> 00:15:07,791
They'll cut you loose after 20 days.

258
00:15:08,916 --> 00:15:09,916
[Morita] Cut me?

259
00:15:10,708 --> 00:15:12,458
Cut loose. Release.

260
00:15:17,166 --> 00:15:19,625
[doctor] Ryota? Ryota, can you hear me?

261
00:15:20,208 --> 00:15:22,250
He's fading fast. Get the monitor.

262
00:15:22,333 --> 00:15:23,583
[nurse 1] Attaching the leads.

263
00:15:23,666 --> 00:15:25,375
[nurse 2] Putting on
the blood pressure cuff.

264
00:15:25,458 --> 00:15:27,250
Stay with us, Ryota.

265
00:15:30,791 --> 00:15:32,208
[woman sniffles softly]

266
00:15:34,791 --> 00:15:35,750
[sniffs]

267
00:15:36,750 --> 00:15:38,000
Ms. Minegishi.

268
00:15:38,583 --> 00:15:39,833
How's your son?

269
00:15:41,583 --> 00:15:43,208
He's still in surgery.

270
00:15:44,208 --> 00:15:45,416
I… I see.

271
00:15:46,916 --> 00:15:47,833
[gasps]

272
00:15:48,458 --> 00:15:49,375
But

273
00:15:50,791 --> 00:15:51,791
my husband…

274
00:15:52,291 --> 00:15:53,291
[sobs]

275
00:15:53,375 --> 00:15:54,375
<i>He…</i>

276
00:15:54,958 --> 00:15:57,083
<i>They said he died instantly.</i>

277
00:15:57,666 --> 00:16:01,708
[sobbing]

278
00:16:05,166 --> 00:16:06,041
[sniffling]

279
00:16:11,708 --> 00:16:13,791
[Kujo] "Japan's number one takoyaki."

280
00:16:14,958 --> 00:16:15,875
What?

281
00:16:15,958 --> 00:16:17,000
[upbeat music playing]

282
00:16:17,083 --> 00:16:19,791
That sign said,
"Japan's number one takoyaki," right?

283
00:16:21,166 --> 00:16:22,625
Oh, did it?

284
00:16:24,250 --> 00:16:26,666
So, maybe we should go give it a try.

285
00:16:27,375 --> 00:16:29,166
Yeah, I don't think so.

286
00:16:29,666 --> 00:16:32,791
Who knows what criteria they're using
to define "Japan's number one."

287
00:16:33,291 --> 00:16:35,375
Isn't it enough they call themselves
"Japan's number one"?

288
00:16:35,458 --> 00:16:38,333
Using phrases like "Japan's number one"
in advertising without evidence

289
00:16:38,416 --> 00:16:40,375
may violate the Act against

290
00:16:40,458 --> 00:16:42,625
Unjustifiable Premiums
and Misleading Representations,

291
00:16:42,708 --> 00:16:44,500
or the Unfair Competition Prevention Act.

292
00:16:44,583 --> 00:16:45,916
So uptight.

293
00:16:46,958 --> 00:16:48,500
That's the University of Tokyo for you.

294
00:16:48,583 --> 00:16:50,291
It's nothing to do with the university.

295
00:16:50,375 --> 00:16:52,666
I just feel uneasy
when things can't be clearly defined.

296
00:16:52,750 --> 00:16:55,625
Okay, then what about
"Japan's funniest osaki"?

297
00:16:56,208 --> 00:16:57,166
What is that?

298
00:16:58,208 --> 00:16:59,166
You don't know?

299
00:16:59,750 --> 00:17:02,625
It's from a comedy duo called "Champions,"

300
00:17:02,708 --> 00:17:06,041
and the straight man calls himself
"Japan's funniest osaki."

301
00:17:06,125 --> 00:17:07,541
Is he breaking the law too?

302
00:17:07,625 --> 00:17:09,375
If he's not the funniest in Japan,
then he is.

303
00:17:09,458 --> 00:17:11,125
Then what about "Nabeatsu of the World"?

304
00:17:11,208 --> 00:17:12,833
Nabeatsu?

305
00:17:12,916 --> 00:17:14,791
He now goes by the name Katsura Sando,

306
00:17:14,875 --> 00:17:17,208
but he used to be part of the duo Jarism.

307
00:17:17,291 --> 00:17:19,416
He was known for his counting gag,

308
00:17:19,500 --> 00:17:22,083
where he acted goofy every time
he reached a multiple of three

309
00:17:22,166 --> 00:17:23,875
or a number containing three.

310
00:17:23,958 --> 00:17:25,750
He called himself "Nabeatsu of the World,"

311
00:17:25,833 --> 00:17:27,541
but that's not claiming to be
the world's number one,

312
00:17:27,625 --> 00:17:29,666
so it doesn't violate
the Act against Unjustifiable…

313
00:17:29,750 --> 00:17:30,791
Hey!

314
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:35,125
What the hell are you guys
rambling on and on about?

315
00:17:35,916 --> 00:17:40,083
I honestly couldn't care less
about takoyaki and comedians.

316
00:17:40,166 --> 00:17:42,833
I'm lying back here, about to go jail!

317
00:17:43,708 --> 00:17:46,416
Can't you just drop it? My God! [groans]

318
00:17:47,916 --> 00:17:51,375
Listen. Mibu obviously likes you
and everything,

319
00:17:51,458 --> 00:17:54,458
and no disrespect,
but do you know what you're doing?

320
00:17:56,458 --> 00:17:58,083
[Kujo] All right. We'll drop it.

321
00:18:00,208 --> 00:18:01,041
Huh?

322
00:18:01,125 --> 00:18:03,958
[Kujo] But then you'll be spending
the next 20 years

323
00:18:04,041 --> 00:18:05,708
without any takoyaki to eat,

324
00:18:05,791 --> 00:18:08,625
without comedy shows to watch
whenever you want.

325
00:18:10,500 --> 00:18:12,458
- So, are you with me?
- Uh.

326
00:18:13,333 --> 00:18:14,375
[Kujo] Or not?

327
00:18:16,833 --> 00:18:19,500
It's up to you.
It's your life. Take control.

328
00:18:24,750 --> 00:18:27,958
CHINESE CUISINE BEIJING RESTAURANT

329
00:18:28,041 --> 00:18:30,166
[Karasuma] So you're the representative
now, Yakushimae.

330
00:18:30,250 --> 00:18:31,083
[Yakushimae] Yeah.

331
00:18:32,041 --> 00:18:35,250
The previous representative
just hit retirement,

332
00:18:35,333 --> 00:18:36,625
so I took over.

333
00:18:37,333 --> 00:18:38,500
Wow…

334
00:18:39,083 --> 00:18:41,375
Your organization helps
ex-felons reintegrate

335
00:18:41,458 --> 00:18:43,041
back into society, am I right?

336
00:18:43,125 --> 00:18:43,958
Mm-hmm.

337
00:18:44,041 --> 00:18:46,958
You can't do that kind of job
without a lot of compassion.

338
00:18:47,708 --> 00:18:50,666
We support them because we don't want
them to commit crimes ever again.

339
00:18:50,750 --> 00:18:51,750
It's not compassion.

340
00:18:51,833 --> 00:18:52,708
What is it?

341
00:18:53,291 --> 00:18:56,208
Mmm… I want a life where
going to a corner store late at night

342
00:18:56,291 --> 00:18:57,875
isn't something to be scared of.

343
00:18:57,958 --> 00:19:00,375
I don't want to become a victim myself.
That's why I do it.

344
00:19:00,875 --> 00:19:01,791
Hmm…

345
00:19:01,875 --> 00:19:04,541
I guess it's just my own way
of preventing crime, you know?

346
00:19:04,625 --> 00:19:06,625
- Hmm.
- [Yakushimae] Hmm.

347
00:19:07,375 --> 00:19:08,416
Excuse me?

348
00:19:08,500 --> 00:19:11,916
Uh, one…
plate of gyoza, pepper pork stir-fry,

349
00:19:12,000 --> 00:19:14,333
and some lettuce and egg-fried rice
to finish it all off.

350
00:19:14,416 --> 00:19:15,416
Oh, I'm good.

351
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:17,333
I was ordering for me.

352
00:19:17,416 --> 00:19:19,833
You'd better eat when you can,
or you won't last, y'know.

353
00:19:19,916 --> 00:19:21,375
- Gotcha.
- [Yakushimae] Two fried rice.

354
00:19:21,458 --> 00:19:23,333
- Comin' right up.
- Thanks very much.

355
00:19:24,666 --> 00:19:25,916
- Mmm.
- Hmm…

356
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:29,833
- So, anyway… You wanted to talk, right?
- Mmm.

357
00:19:29,916 --> 00:19:30,791
What you got?

358
00:19:30,875 --> 00:19:33,541
I wanted to thank you
for introducing me to Mr. Kujo.

359
00:19:33,625 --> 00:19:34,583
[Yakushimae] Mmm.

360
00:19:34,666 --> 00:19:35,625
How'd it go?

361
00:19:36,500 --> 00:19:39,583
Mmm, I don't know.
I'm in a trial period now, I guess.

362
00:19:40,083 --> 00:19:41,541
Are you really gonna stay?

363
00:19:41,625 --> 00:19:46,041
Seriously, why work for a lawyer
who's liable to be disbarred any day?

364
00:19:46,541 --> 00:19:47,875
I want to find out

365
00:19:47,958 --> 00:19:52,166
whether Kujo's actually
a good lawyer or if he's a bad one.

366
00:19:53,333 --> 00:19:55,041
[inquisitive music playing]

367
00:19:55,666 --> 00:19:57,750
Now you want to know why
I want to find out.

368
00:19:57,833 --> 00:20:00,000
I'm making it sound like
there's some big backstory.

369
00:20:02,041 --> 00:20:03,375
[Yakushimae] Good lawyers

370
00:20:04,125 --> 00:20:05,666
are bad people.

371
00:20:05,750 --> 00:20:06,833
Huh?

372
00:20:07,500 --> 00:20:08,625
That's my own theory.

373
00:20:09,208 --> 00:20:10,083
Including Mr. Kujo?

374
00:20:10,166 --> 00:20:13,250
Isn't that what you're trying to find out?
For whatever reason.

375
00:20:13,875 --> 00:20:14,791
Yeah.

376
00:20:14,875 --> 00:20:17,625
Well, if you do find out, let me know.

377
00:20:18,625 --> 00:20:19,666
Yes, ma'am.

378
00:20:21,916 --> 00:20:23,375
By the way, did you know

379
00:20:23,458 --> 00:20:25,958
that he kept his ex-wife's last name
even after the divorce?

380
00:20:26,041 --> 00:20:27,583
What? No.

381
00:20:27,666 --> 00:20:29,583
And they have a daughter together too.

382
00:20:29,666 --> 00:20:33,250
And when they got divorced,
he gave them all his assets.

383
00:20:33,333 --> 00:20:35,625
Mmm, he is a good person.

384
00:20:36,125 --> 00:20:38,500
Well, then that would mean he is, um…

385
00:20:38,583 --> 00:20:40,291
Here. Here's your gyoza.

386
00:20:40,375 --> 00:20:42,875
Ah! That was fast! Thank you.

387
00:20:42,958 --> 00:20:43,875
Enjoy.

388
00:20:43,958 --> 00:20:45,333
- Oh, uh, can you, um…
- Oh.

389
00:20:45,416 --> 00:20:46,583
Ah!

390
00:20:46,666 --> 00:20:48,416
Boss, it's delicious.

391
00:20:48,500 --> 00:20:49,333
Thank you.

392
00:20:49,416 --> 00:20:50,416
[Yakushimae laughs]

393
00:20:51,125 --> 00:20:53,875
Mmm. Oh my God! So good, so good, so good!

394
00:20:56,666 --> 00:20:57,666
[cat meowing]

395
00:21:06,208 --> 00:21:07,208
Good morning.

396
00:21:08,041 --> 00:21:08,958
Good morning.

397
00:21:10,208 --> 00:21:11,833
Is that your breakfast, sir?

398
00:21:11,916 --> 00:21:12,750
Yep.

399
00:21:15,750 --> 00:21:16,708
[Mibu sighs]

400
00:21:18,541 --> 00:21:19,500
Well…

401
00:21:20,125 --> 00:21:21,458
Please take care of Morita.

402
00:21:21,541 --> 00:21:22,375
I will.

403
00:21:26,708 --> 00:21:29,625
Attorney Karasuma,
I'm counting on you too.

404
00:21:29,708 --> 00:21:30,541
Huh?

405
00:21:31,875 --> 00:21:32,708
Oh.

406
00:21:33,208 --> 00:21:34,041
Sure.

407
00:21:43,625 --> 00:21:45,958
What exactly does Mr. Mibu do
for a living?

408
00:21:46,750 --> 00:21:48,750
Officially, he runs an auto repair shop,

409
00:21:48,833 --> 00:21:52,458
but he appears to have connections
with less than savory characters.

410
00:21:52,958 --> 00:21:55,583
Do we really need to get along
with people like that?

411
00:21:57,041 --> 00:21:59,250
I don't know.
Does it look like we're getting along?

412
00:22:00,791 --> 00:22:01,666
Yeah.

413
00:22:02,916 --> 00:22:04,875
Oh, speaking of which…

414
00:22:07,041 --> 00:22:10,083
Mr. Morita's police interview.
How'd it go?

415
00:22:12,666 --> 00:22:14,541
It all went as well as expected.

416
00:22:14,625 --> 00:22:15,666
[melancholy music playing]

417
00:22:15,750 --> 00:22:17,458
All right. Let's go.

418
00:22:17,541 --> 00:22:18,625
[boy] Yay!

419
00:22:19,541 --> 00:22:22,708
[Kujo] <i>The victims were a father,</i>
<i>Masato Minegishi, aged 35,</i>

420
00:22:22,791 --> 00:22:24,458
<i>and his son, Ryota, age 6.</i>

421
00:22:24,541 --> 00:22:25,583
NURSERY

422
00:22:25,666 --> 00:22:27,916
<i>The accident happened</i>
<i>on their way home from daycare.</i>

423
00:22:29,041 --> 00:22:31,166
<i>It seems the father</i>
<i>had been suffering from depression</i>

424
00:22:31,250 --> 00:22:32,583
<i>and was on leave from work.</i>

425
00:22:33,166 --> 00:22:34,291
Depression?

426
00:22:35,541 --> 00:22:37,041
And how's the father doing now?

427
00:22:37,125 --> 00:22:38,583
He passed away.

428
00:22:39,916 --> 00:22:42,333
But there's something
that caught my attention.

429
00:22:42,833 --> 00:22:45,291
The accident was captured
by Mr. Morita's dashcam,

430
00:22:45,375 --> 00:22:46,916
and the victim's bicycle

431
00:22:47,000 --> 00:22:48,500
was already lying on the ground.

432
00:22:48,583 --> 00:22:50,125
It was already on the ground?

433
00:22:50,208 --> 00:22:52,125
Furthermore,
according to the investigation

434
00:22:52,208 --> 00:22:56,083
and the medical examiner,
the child was bleeding significantly,

435
00:22:56,166 --> 00:22:58,625
whereas there were no signs of bleeding
or other vital reactions

436
00:22:58,708 --> 00:23:00,166
observed in the father's body.

437
00:23:00,250 --> 00:23:01,333
Whoa.

438
00:23:01,416 --> 00:23:03,416
If he had been alive when he was hit,

439
00:23:03,500 --> 00:23:06,041
there would have been bleeding
from his injuries, right?

440
00:23:06,125 --> 00:23:07,375
Yeah, that's right.

441
00:23:07,458 --> 00:23:08,625
Something…

442
00:23:09,750 --> 00:23:11,583
something felt off, so I looked into it

443
00:23:11,666 --> 00:23:14,791
and requested the father's medical records
from the area hospital.

444
00:23:17,291 --> 00:23:21,291
He's been rushed to the hospital several
times recently due to heart conditions,

445
00:23:21,375 --> 00:23:24,833
and he's been prescribed medication
for those same conditions.

446
00:23:25,625 --> 00:23:26,916
Heart conditions?

447
00:23:30,375 --> 00:23:34,333
What if the father actually had
a heart attack, collapsed on the road,

448
00:23:34,833 --> 00:23:37,791
and was already dead
when he was hit by Mr. Morita?

449
00:23:39,791 --> 00:23:40,625
Wait. Hold on.

450
00:23:41,250 --> 00:23:44,125
Are you saying that the father's death
had nothing to do with the accident,

451
00:23:44,208 --> 00:23:45,375
Mr. Kujo?

452
00:23:45,458 --> 00:23:46,791
If that's the case,

453
00:23:47,583 --> 00:23:49,833
we're looking at desecration
of a corpse due to negligence,

454
00:23:49,916 --> 00:23:51,500
which isn't a criminal offense.

455
00:23:51,583 --> 00:23:53,125
If he was already dead,

456
00:23:53,208 --> 00:23:55,166
it isn't negligent driving
causing death either.

457
00:23:55,250 --> 00:23:58,291
But Morita had been drinking all morning
and was playing a game on his phone

458
00:23:58,375 --> 00:23:59,958
when he ran into them.

459
00:24:00,041 --> 00:24:03,291
Oh, you're right.
I agree. He's a total scumbag.

460
00:24:03,375 --> 00:24:05,708
All right, so you think so too. Then we--

461
00:24:05,791 --> 00:24:09,458
But whether or not we think he's a scumbag
is irrelevant to the case.

462
00:24:09,541 --> 00:24:13,250
What is relevant is when Morita hit him,
was the father alive or was he dead?

463
00:24:13,333 --> 00:24:14,166
That's the question.

464
00:24:18,083 --> 00:24:19,083
And how…

465
00:24:19,833 --> 00:24:21,208
What about the kid? How's he doing?

466
00:24:24,708 --> 00:24:26,791
There were no life-threatening injuries.

467
00:24:28,625 --> 00:24:29,458
But his…

468
00:24:29,541 --> 00:24:31,541
[machines beeping and whooshing softly]

469
00:24:32,833 --> 00:24:34,916
<i>His left leg was amputated.</i>

470
00:24:43,375 --> 00:24:44,500
[Ms. Minegishi] Ryota!

471
00:24:46,541 --> 00:24:47,875
[sobbing]

472
00:24:49,750 --> 00:24:51,666
[voice breaking] I'm sorry.

473
00:24:53,583 --> 00:24:54,416
[sobs]

474
00:24:54,500 --> 00:24:56,333
I'm sorry.

475
00:24:56,416 --> 00:24:57,833
[sobbing]

476
00:24:57,916 --> 00:24:59,916
[melancholy music playing]

477
00:25:01,958 --> 00:25:03,291
[snores]

478
00:25:29,166 --> 00:25:30,041
[judge] <i>The decision.</i>

479
00:25:30,125 --> 00:25:31,041
COURTHOUSE

480
00:25:31,125 --> 00:25:34,791
<i>The defendant is sentenced to one year</i>
<i>and eight months of imprisonment.</i>

481
00:25:35,291 --> 00:25:38,833
The execution of this sentence
shall be suspended for three years

482
00:25:38,916 --> 00:25:41,416
from the date on which this ruling
becomes final and binding.

483
00:25:41,500 --> 00:25:42,666
[melancholy music continues]

484
00:25:42,750 --> 00:25:43,625
Huh?

485
00:25:44,166 --> 00:25:47,000
For real? Suspended sentence?

486
00:25:47,083 --> 00:25:48,583
Hey, I'm not being sent to the cooler?

487
00:25:48,666 --> 00:25:50,833
[judge] Defendant, please remain silent.

488
00:25:50,916 --> 00:25:51,833
[gasps with excitement]

489
00:25:51,916 --> 00:25:55,000
[judge] The reasons for
the court's decision are as follows.

490
00:25:56,291 --> 00:26:01,166
On April 1st, 2025,
the defendant, Mr. Morita,

491
00:26:01,666 --> 00:26:03,958
was driving a standard passenger vehicle…

492
00:26:04,041 --> 00:26:04,875
[sobbing quietly]

493
00:26:04,958 --> 00:26:08,916
…on the road near 6-14-5,
Koto Ward, Tokyo.

494
00:26:09,833 --> 00:26:13,958
He was driving from the southwest
to the northeast.

495
00:26:14,541 --> 00:26:16,541
[upbeat music playing]

496
00:26:18,625 --> 00:26:21,375
Mr. Kujo, thanks a lot, man!

497
00:26:21,458 --> 00:26:22,375
[laughs]

498
00:26:22,458 --> 00:26:24,458
- [man] Morita!
- Whoa!

499
00:26:24,541 --> 00:26:28,208
Senpai said he'll treat you to yakiniku
at the club to celebrate your awesome win!

500
00:26:28,291 --> 00:26:29,916
What? For real? Yakiniku?

501
00:26:30,000 --> 00:26:32,750
- [laughs]
- [Morita] That's amazing! Meat!

502
00:26:32,833 --> 00:26:34,833
Man, I'm dying for a cold beer too!

503
00:26:34,916 --> 00:26:36,541
Jail food sucks.

504
00:26:40,708 --> 00:26:44,250
The accident occurred postmortem,
so Morita's not liable for it.

505
00:26:44,750 --> 00:26:45,708
And…

506
00:26:46,791 --> 00:26:50,000
Apparently, they were talked into settling
for the standard terms

507
00:26:50,083 --> 00:26:52,375
by the insurance company
since they didn't hire a lawyer.

508
00:26:53,375 --> 00:26:54,708
The child loses a leg.

509
00:26:55,458 --> 00:26:59,041
Even though it's a catastrophic injury,
they're only getting 40 million yen.

510
00:27:00,583 --> 00:27:03,375
Ignorance is the worst disability
there is.

511
00:27:03,458 --> 00:27:06,041
Mr. Kujo,
how could you say something so cold?

512
00:27:06,125 --> 00:27:07,666
For Ryota and his mother…

513
00:27:08,375 --> 00:27:10,625
For any child to lose a parent like that.

514
00:27:12,041 --> 00:27:14,166
If we'd been on their side instead,

515
00:27:14,250 --> 00:27:15,708
they'd have over 100 million

516
00:27:15,791 --> 00:27:18,375
in lost future earnings,
plus disability compensation.

517
00:27:18,458 --> 00:27:22,250
And we could've claimed another 5 million
for treatments and rehabilitation.

518
00:27:22,750 --> 00:27:26,708
They crossed paths with someone like that,
and their lives are irreparably changed--

519
00:27:26,791 --> 00:27:28,375
Mr. Karasuma, listen.

520
00:27:28,458 --> 00:27:31,958
A lawyer's not supposed to act
based on their personal convictions.

521
00:27:32,458 --> 00:27:35,041
It's best to keep the law and morality
separate in your thinking.

522
00:27:35,125 --> 00:27:37,541
Even if something is morally unforgivable,

523
00:27:37,625 --> 00:27:40,125
a lawyer's responsibility
is to protect their client.

524
00:27:41,625 --> 00:27:42,625
However,

525
00:27:43,916 --> 00:27:48,250
it's true that when you protect
your client, you'll hurt the other side.

526
00:27:50,000 --> 00:27:53,750
Part of this profession is that we carry
the burden of that sin

527
00:27:53,833 --> 00:27:55,125
throughout our lives.

528
00:27:56,625 --> 00:27:58,625
[upbeat music playing]

529
00:28:04,041 --> 00:28:06,166
You agreed to defend a known criminal?
Why would you?

530
00:28:06,250 --> 00:28:08,416
- How much did you get paid for this case?
- One question!

531
00:28:08,500 --> 00:28:10,250
- Excuse me, Attorney Kujo!
- Why this client?

532
00:28:10,333 --> 00:28:13,125
If I'm ever in deep trouble,
I'll be counting on you to defend me.

533
00:28:13,208 --> 00:28:14,500
[overlapping questions]

534
00:28:55,750 --> 00:28:58,625
CIVIL TRAFFIC ACCIDENT CLAIMS: STANDARDS
FOR CALCULATING DAMAGES VOLUME 2

535
00:29:00,791 --> 00:29:02,958
VERDICTS FOR NEGLIGENT DRIVING
CAUSING DEATH OR INJURY

536
00:29:07,583 --> 00:29:09,583
[music fades]

537
00:29:30,500 --> 00:29:31,833
Yakushimae?

538
00:29:33,041 --> 00:29:35,291
[physiotherapist] Bit by bit. Good.

539
00:29:35,375 --> 00:29:37,125
[Ms. Minegishi] As I mentioned
over the phone…

540
00:29:37,208 --> 00:29:38,333
There you go.

541
00:29:38,416 --> 00:29:40,166
…I don't think it's possible.

542
00:29:41,791 --> 00:29:45,625
Yes, I understand that once a settlement
is finalized with an insurance company,

543
00:29:45,708 --> 00:29:48,250
it's usually very difficult
to have it overturned.

544
00:29:48,750 --> 00:29:52,166
However, maybe you could file a lawsuit

545
00:29:52,250 --> 00:29:53,750
regarding your son's insurance claim.

546
00:29:57,666 --> 00:29:59,708
There's a lawyer I know
who can help you with that.

547
00:30:00,583 --> 00:30:01,958
I don't think so.

548
00:30:04,833 --> 00:30:06,500
I've lost the will to keep going.

549
00:30:06,583 --> 00:30:08,333
That might be the case for you…

550
00:30:11,250 --> 00:30:12,750
but what about Ryota?

551
00:30:18,166 --> 00:30:20,458
He has his whole life ahead of him.

552
00:30:20,541 --> 00:30:21,875
[Ryota grunts]

553
00:30:24,708 --> 00:30:26,041
[Yakushimae] For his sake,

554
00:30:27,250 --> 00:30:28,541
let's give it a try.

555
00:30:59,750 --> 00:31:01,666
I gave her the message.

556
00:31:01,750 --> 00:31:02,833
What?

557
00:31:02,916 --> 00:31:04,041
Tell Kujo

558
00:31:04,583 --> 00:31:07,583
I passed on his message
exactly as he told me.

559
00:31:12,291 --> 00:31:14,208
[inquisitive music playing]

560
00:31:15,291 --> 00:31:17,583
Let's do just a bit more, okay?

561
00:31:18,083 --> 00:31:19,583
- Thank you.
- [physical therapist] Sure.

562
00:31:34,041 --> 00:31:36,125
I saw Yakushimae at the hospital.

563
00:31:37,416 --> 00:31:39,375
You asked her to do that, didn't you?

564
00:31:39,875 --> 00:31:43,625
You asked her to tell Mrs. Minegishi
to file a lawsuit for her son.

565
00:31:45,125 --> 00:31:49,125
You even wrote a referral letter
to your mentor, Attorney Nagaragi.

566
00:31:50,458 --> 00:31:55,041
I don't get it. If you wanted to help,
why not just refuse to defend the bad guy?

567
00:31:56,541 --> 00:31:59,375
It doesn't make any sense.
What is it that's driving you?

568
00:32:00,250 --> 00:32:01,500
[Kujo] Mr. Karasuma,

569
00:32:02,916 --> 00:32:04,166
I'll say it again.

570
00:32:05,583 --> 00:32:07,833
A lawyer upholds human rights,

571
00:32:07,916 --> 00:32:10,541
and a lawyer's duty is
to protect their client.

572
00:32:10,625 --> 00:32:13,291
I'm not looking for the textbook answer.

573
00:32:13,958 --> 00:32:16,083
I want to know what motivates you.

574
00:32:23,958 --> 00:32:26,416
Why did you become a lawyer, Mr. Kujo?

575
00:32:29,541 --> 00:32:31,916
Are you interviewing me again?

576
00:32:37,250 --> 00:32:39,791
All right.
Let me ask you the same question.

577
00:32:40,708 --> 00:32:43,375
Why did you become a lawyer, Mr. Karasuma?

578
00:32:44,458 --> 00:32:46,416
Top of your class in university.

579
00:32:46,500 --> 00:32:48,708
You could've become an elite bureaucrat.

580
00:32:51,916 --> 00:32:53,791
It started a long time ago.

581
00:32:53,875 --> 00:32:55,416
There was a trial I attended

582
00:32:56,166 --> 00:32:57,333
<i>18 years ago.</i>

583
00:32:57,833 --> 00:33:00,125
<i>A murder case where</i>
<i>the defendant had committed the crime</i>

584
00:33:00,208 --> 00:33:02,041
<i>because he wanted the death penalty.</i>

585
00:33:02,125 --> 00:33:04,375
<i>I was still in elementary school,</i>

586
00:33:04,958 --> 00:33:07,708
and I couldn't understand
either the motives

587
00:33:07,791 --> 00:33:10,750
or the emotions
of the killer or the victims.

588
00:33:10,833 --> 00:33:13,625
The only thing that made any sense
to me was the law.

589
00:33:16,000 --> 00:33:17,041
I get that.

590
00:33:18,833 --> 00:33:22,208
So I decided to seek the meaning of life

591
00:33:22,291 --> 00:33:25,375
through learning about the law
and everything connected to it.

592
00:33:29,250 --> 00:33:30,291
I understand.

593
00:33:32,166 --> 00:33:33,375
I remember…

594
00:33:36,916 --> 00:33:38,375
[music fades]

595
00:33:41,166 --> 00:33:43,125
I remember that trial. I was there.

596
00:33:44,125 --> 00:33:45,250
[Karasuma] I know.

597
00:33:46,333 --> 00:33:47,583
That's why I'm here.

598
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:51,833
I came here so I can understand you.

599
00:33:55,666 --> 00:33:57,833
If it's okay, I'll stick around for a bit.

600
00:34:04,750 --> 00:34:05,708
Okay. Sure.

601
00:34:10,125 --> 00:34:12,125
[inquisitive music playing]

602
00:34:39,583 --> 00:34:40,750
[man] Hey, Sogabe.

603
00:34:46,041 --> 00:34:47,000
Veggies.

604
00:34:49,708 --> 00:34:50,791
Go on. Go.

605
00:34:50,875 --> 00:34:51,708
[Sogabe] Okay.

606
00:34:52,291 --> 00:34:53,166
Later.

607
00:35:06,250 --> 00:35:07,375
[man] Excuse me!

608
00:35:10,291 --> 00:35:12,000
- You have a moment?
- Huh?

609
00:35:12,500 --> 00:35:14,291
[cop 1] What you… What you got there?

610
00:35:15,708 --> 00:35:17,958
Uh, well, it's just candy.

611
00:35:18,041 --> 00:35:20,083
Do you mind if we have a look
inside the bag, sir?

612
00:35:20,166 --> 00:35:21,500
I told you, it's just candy.

613
00:35:21,583 --> 00:35:23,458
- We just want to confirm that.
- Oh, I'm so sorry.

614
00:35:23,541 --> 00:35:25,791
- Don't, don't get mad at me, okay?
- [cop 1] I'm not mad.

615
00:35:25,875 --> 00:35:28,708
- I'm sorry. I'm sorry.
- [Kujo] Excuse me. May I have a moment?

616
00:35:28,791 --> 00:35:30,625
[Sogabe] I'm sorry. I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

617
00:35:30,708 --> 00:35:31,916
What are you doing?

618
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:33,708
You wanna get charged with obstruction?

619
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:36,750
Filming for a legitimate reason

620
00:35:36,833 --> 00:35:40,416
is not considered obstructing
the performance of public duty.

621
00:35:40,500 --> 00:35:44,083
I'm preserving evidence in case
there's an illegal search and seizure.

622
00:35:44,166 --> 00:35:45,708
Who the hell do you think you are, huh?

623
00:35:45,791 --> 00:35:46,875
[cell phone chimes]

624
00:35:48,458 --> 00:35:52,291
A good lawyer, but a… a bad person.

625
00:35:54,875 --> 00:35:56,875
[closing theme song playing]
